TWO taxi drivers have shot and killed in Umlazi south of Durban on Tuesday night. The 43 and 44 year-olds, under MNR taxi associations, were killed inside their taxis in a separate incidents. Mandla Duma who is the owner of the taxi in which one of the drivers were killed, said he had no idea why their drivers were killed. But Daily Sun was reliably informed that MNR Association is in the war over route with Engonyameni Taxi Association. The source said the incident came after MNR taxi bosses prevented Engonyameni taxis from using the Durban route which passes through Umlazi. The incident forced drivers to down keys fearing for their lives. One of the drivers who asked not to be named said they decided to stop working because they fear for the for lives. He said route disputes are not their problem but they end up being victims. Cops spokesman Lieutenant Colonel Thulani Zwane said: "We can confirm two counts of murder are being investigated by Umlazi SAPS after two taxi drivers were killed in two separate incidents in Umlazi. It is alleged that on 16 July 2019 at 18:00, a 43-year-old man was shot and killed while at D section in Umlazi. He sustained a gunshot wound to the head and was declared dead at the scene." In another incident at 18:35, a 44-year-old man was allegedly shot and killed at M section in Umlazi by unknown suspects. He sustained gunshot wounds to the back and shoulder and was declared dead at the scene. "We are appealing to anyone who might have information about the suspects involved in both incidents to contact the local police or 080010111." 